      <!-- Free vs free tier -->
      <section id="free-vs-free-tier">
        <div class="grid gap-8 lg:grid-cols-12">
          <div class="lg:col-span-4">
            <span class="eyebrow">Terminology</span>
            <h2 class="anchor-top !mt-3">Free vs Free Tier: An Important Distinction</h2>
          </div>
          <div class="lg:col-span-8 space-y-4">
            <p><strong>"Free" in the context of GEO tools means two different things, and conflating them will lead to disappointment.</strong></p>
            <p>A <strong>genuinely free tool</strong> is one with no meaningful functional restriction relative to its core GEO use case. Google's Rich Results Test is an example: it validates your structured data completely, without a query limit, a subscription requirement, or a feature gate. You can use it indefinitely without paying anything and receive the full value it offers. Wikipedia and Wikidata editing interfaces are free. Google Search Console is free. Manual AI spot-checking using ChatGPT's free plan is free.</p>
            <p>A <strong>free tier</strong> is a restricted version of a paid product. Most dedicated GEO monitoring platforms offer free tiers that allow a limited number of monitored queries, a capped number of AI platforms, or a restricted history window. These are valuable for getting started — they allow you to experience the product and establish a partial baseline — but they are specifically designed to convert you to a paying customer as your needs grow. That is not a criticism; it is simply the nature of the business model. Understand the ceiling before you rely on a free tier as your primary measurement infrastructure.</p>
            <p>This page covers both categories, clearly labelled. For the budget-conscious angle — what you can accomplish for under £100 per month — see the section on <a href="#when-to-upgrade" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">when to upgrade</a>. For a full overview of the paid tool landscape, the <a href="/geo-tools/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO Tools hub</a> and the <a href="/best-geo-tools-2026/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">2026 best GEO tools roundup</a> cover the full range.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Manual spot-checking -->
      <section id="manual-spot-checking">
        <span class="eyebrow">Method 1 — Genuinely free</span>
        <h2 class="anchor-top !mt-3">Manual AI Spot-Checking</h2>
        <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-ink-300 leading-relaxed"><strong>Manual spot-checking is the most accessible way to begin measuring AI visibility: query ChatGPT, Perplexity, and Gemini directly with your most important target prompts, and record what you find.</strong></p>

        <div class="mt-8 space-y-6">

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-semibold text-ink-50">How to Run a Manual Baseline Check</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">Open each AI platform — ChatGPT (free plan), Perplexity (free), and Gemini (free) — and run the same ten to twenty prompts across all three. Use prompts that reflect how your target customers actually ask questions: category questions ("what is the best [product type] for [use case]"), comparison prompts ("compare [your brand] and [competitor]"), and recommendation prompts ("who should I use for [service]"). Record the full response for each prompt, note whether your brand appears, how it is described, which competitors appear alongside it, and which source URLs are cited. A simple spreadsheet with columns for platform, prompt, brand appeared (yes/no), description used, competitors mentioned, and sources cited is adequate.</p>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">Run each prompt two or three times and note any variation — AI responses are probabilistic, so a single run is not representative. This variability is precisely why a manual method cannot replace systematic monitoring for ongoing measurement, but it is sufficient to establish a directional baseline and identify obvious gaps.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-semibold text-ink-50">What Manual Checks Can and Cannot Tell You</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300"><strong>Manual spot-checking is effective for qualitative discovery: identifying how your brand is described, which competitors appear regularly, whether obvious factual inaccuracies exist, and which source URLs AI platforms are citing for your category.</strong> These qualitative findings are actionable: they tell you what to correct, which sources to strengthen, and how your positioning is being characterised by AI systems to potential customers.</p>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">What manual checks cannot reliably tell you is your statistical citation rate — the percentage of relevant queries on which your brand appears. AI responses vary significantly between runs. A citation observed once is not evidence of reliable inclusion; an absence on a single run is not evidence of exclusion. For that kind of measurement, a dedicated monitoring tool running multiple samples across a consistent prompt set is required. Manual checks are a starting point, not a measurement system.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-semibold text-ink-50">Using AI Assistants as Free Optimisation Tools</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300"><strong>The free plans of Claude, ChatGPT, and Gemini are themselves useful as GEO optimisation tools: they can restructure existing content according to citation-friendly patterns at no cost.</strong> The method is simple: paste a section of your existing content into the assistant and ask it to rewrite it to lead with a bold declarative statement, add a concise FAQ block, and structure the key claims as direct answers to common questions. The practitioner's job is to provide subject matter accuracy and editorial judgement; the assistant handles the restructuring. For teams without a dedicated content tool budget, this represents a meaningful free optimisation capability — used correctly, it is not a shortcut but a legitimate restructuring workflow.</p>
          </div>

        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Schema tools -->
      <section id="schema-tools">
        <span class="eyebrow">Method 2 — Genuinely free</span>
        <h2 class="anchor-top !mt-3">Free Structured Data and Schema Tools</h2>
        <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-ink-300 leading-relaxed"><strong>Structured data validation is an area where free tools provide complete, production-quality capability — there is no meaningful gap between the free and paid options for this task.</strong></p>

        <div class="mt-8 space-y-6">

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-semibold text-ink-50">Google Rich Results Test</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-500 font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wide">Genuinely free — no usage limit</p>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300"><strong>Google's Rich Results Test validates your JSON-LD schema against Google's own interpretation of Schema.org types — the most important validation target for GEO purposes.</strong> It accepts a URL or pasted code, identifies which schema types are present, flags syntax errors and missing required fields, and shows a preview of how Google's systems interpret your markup. For the schema types most relevant to GEO — Article, FAQPage, BreadcrumbList, Organization — it provides complete validation at no cost. Run it on every significant content page before and after any schema implementation work.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-semibold text-ink-50">Schema.org Validator</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-500 font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wide">Genuinely free — no usage limit</p>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300"><strong>The official Schema.org validator checks structured data markup against the Schema.org specification directly, independent of any specific search engine's interpretation.</strong> It is particularly useful for catching type hierarchy errors and property misuse that may not surface in Google's test (which focuses on rich result eligibility rather than full specification compliance). Use it alongside the Rich Results Test for thorough validation: Google's tool tells you whether your schema will produce rich results; the Schema.org validator tells you whether your schema accurately represents what it claims to represent. Both are free and require no account.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-semibold text-ink-50">Google's Structured Data Markup Helper</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-500 font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wide">Genuinely free — no usage limit</p>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300"><strong>For teams adding schema markup for the first time, Google's Structured Data Markup Helper is a free guided tool that generates valid JSON-LD by tagging elements on a live page.</strong> It is a generation tool, not a validator: it produces schema code that you then paste into your page's head. The output covers common schema types and is syntactically valid, though you should review and adjust it to ensure accuracy of the factual claims it makes about your content. It is a practical starting point for teams without a developer who can write schema from scratch.</p>
          </div>

        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Entity methods -->
      <section id="entity-methods">
        <span class="eyebrow">Method 3 — Genuinely free</span>
        <h2 class="anchor-top !mt-3">Free Entity and Knowledge Graph Methods</h2>
        <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-ink-300 leading-relaxed"><strong>Entity work — improving how AI models recognise and describe your brand — is one of the highest-leverage GEO activities, and its most important elements can be started without any tool spend.</strong></p>

        <div class="mt-8 space-y-6">

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-semibold text-ink-50">Wikipedia and Wikidata Review and Improvement</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-500 font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wide">Genuinely free — editorial effort required</p>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300"><strong>Large language models draw heavily on Wikipedia and Wikidata when constructing factual descriptions of organisations — reviewing and improving your presence on both platforms is free, impactful, and underutilised by most brands.</strong> Begin with a check of whether your organisation has a Wikipedia article, whether it meets Wikipedia's notability standards (third-party, independent sources are required), and whether the content is accurate, up to date, and well-sourced. If an article exists but is thin or poorly structured, improving it through Wikipedia's editing interface is free. Wikidata records — the structured data counterpart to Wikipedia — should include your organisation's founding date, headquarters location, legal name, industry, and key relationships. These are the structured attributes that LLMs reference when generating factual summaries. No tool is required to check or improve these; only Wikipedia's and Wikidata's own interfaces.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-semibold text-ink-50">Google Knowledge Panel Review</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-500 font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wide">Genuinely free — requires Google Business Profile</p>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300"><strong>Your Google Knowledge Panel is a direct window into how Google's systems — and, by extension, many AI models — characterise your brand.</strong> Search your brand name and examine the panel that appears: does it display the correct description, category, contact details, and associated URLs? Is the primary image appropriate? Are the most important facts about your organisation present and accurate? Claiming your Knowledge Panel through Google Search Console or Google Business Profile is free and allows you to suggest corrections. For <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">generative engine optimisation</a> purposes, the Knowledge Panel is a proxy for entity clarity: if Google cannot construct a clean, accurate knowledge panel for your brand, AI systems will likely share a similar characterisation gap.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-semibold text-ink-50">Authoritative External Citation Audit</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-500 font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wide">Genuinely free — time investment required</p>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300"><strong>An authoritative external citation audit assesses whether your brand is mentioned, quoted, or described by the types of third-party sources that AI models treat as credible references.</strong> Industry association databases, government supplier registers, press coverage in publications with genuine editorial standards, academic citations, and professional directories are the sources that carry entity weight. A manual audit — searching for your brand name in these contexts and identifying obvious gaps — costs nothing and frequently surfaces the same gaps that a dedicated entity analysis tool would flag. The fix for these gaps is editorial work (earning coverage, submitting accurate information to relevant databases, ensuring professional directories contain current details), not additional software.</p>
          </div>

        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Free-tier platforms -->
      <section id="free-tier-platforms">
        <span class="eyebrow">Method 4 — Free tier</span>
        <h2 class="anchor-top !mt-3">Free-Tier Monitoring Platforms</h2>
        <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-ink-300 leading-relaxed"><strong>Several dedicated GEO monitoring platforms offer free tiers that allow limited citation tracking — useful for establishing a partial baseline and experiencing the product before committing to a paid plan.</strong></p>

        <div class="mt-8 space-y-6">

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-semibold text-ink-50">Entry-Level Tiers of Dedicated GEO Platforms</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300"><strong>Platforms such as Otterly.ai and similar dedicated GEO monitoring tools have offered free or entry-level tiers that provide access to a limited number of tracked prompts and AI platforms.</strong> The value of these tiers is genuine but bounded: you can monitor a small set of your most important queries and observe how your brand appears across the covered platforms. What you cannot do on free tiers is run the query volume, retain the history depth, or access the competitive benchmarking features that make a monitoring platform operationally useful for an ongoing programme.</p>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">Check current free tier terms directly with each vendor. Free tier availability, query limits, and platform coverage in free plans change regularly as platforms evolve their pricing models. What is described here reflects the general category pattern, not guaranteed current terms for any specific product.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-semibold text-ink-50">Google Search Console as an Indirect GEO Signal</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-500 font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wide">Genuinely free — indirect GEO utility</p>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300"><strong>Google Search Console does not measure AI citation frequency, but it provides free data that is indirectly useful for a GEO programme.</strong> Monitoring traffic to pages you have restructured for GEO can surface whether Google AI Overviews are driving referral clicks — an indirect indicator of improved AI visibility for that page. GSC's performance data on search queries also informs the content topical coverage decisions that underpin GEO. It belongs in any practitioner's free toolkit, with the explicit understanding that it measures traditional organic search and AI overview referral traffic, not AI citation rates across the broader platform landscape.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-semibold text-ink-50">Semrush and Ahrefs Free Plans</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-500 font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wide">Free tier — restricted functionality</p>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300"><strong>Both Semrush and Ahrefs offer restricted free access that provides limited brand mention monitoring and content analysis data useful as part of a free GEO toolkit.</strong> Semrush's free tier allows a limited number of daily searches; Ahrefs' free tools include a backlink checker and limited site audit. Neither free plan gives meaningful access to the AI visibility features these platforms have added in 2025–26. Their GEO utility at the free tier is confined to the foundational work: content gap analysis, basic technical audit, and brand mention data at limited volume. Useful as supporting tools; not a substitute for dedicated GEO measurement.</p>
          </div>

        </div>
      </section>

