      <!-- When to upgrade -->
      <section id="when-to-upgrade">
        <span class="eyebrow">Budget planning</span>
        <h2 class="anchor-top !mt-3">When to Move Beyond Free: The Under-£100 Decision</h2>
        <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-ink-300 leading-relaxed"><strong>Free tools provide a genuine starting point, but there is a ceiling — and recognising it is as important as using the free tools effectively.</strong></p>

        <div class="mt-8 space-y-6">

          <div class="card p-6 border-l-2 border-l-[var(--accent)]">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-ink-50">What free tools cannot do well</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">Systematic citation frequency tracking — measuring your citation rate across a consistent prompt set on a weekly cadence across four or more AI platforms — is not achievable with free tools alone. Manual spot-checking produces useful qualitative evidence but not statistically reliable frequency data. This matters because GEO improvement requires measurement: if you cannot reliably track whether your citation rate is moving, you cannot evaluate whether your optimisation work is having effect. Free tools give you the starting conditions; they do not give you an ongoing measurement programme.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6 border-l-2 border-l-[var(--accent)]">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-ink-50">The under-£100 per month entry point</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">Entry-level tiers of dedicated GEO monitoring platforms are available for approximately £50–£100 per month at current pricing (verify with vendors directly, as this changes). At this price point, you gain scheduled citation tracking across the core AI platforms, basic competitive benchmarking, and historical data retention that lets you identify trends. This is a meaningful capability upgrade from the free tier and is appropriate once you have an active optimisation process — content being published and structured, schema being improved, entity work under way — that you need to measure. Investing in monitoring before you have an optimisation process gives you data you cannot act on; investing after gives you accountability for the work you are doing.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6 border-l-2 border-l-[var(--accent)]">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-ink-50">The right sequencing decision</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">Use free tools to run your initial baseline check, validate your schema, review your entity presence, and fix your most obvious structural issues. If those actions surface significant gaps — which they usually will — address them before paying for ongoing monitoring. Once you have a process (regular content improvement, schema maintenance, entity monitoring) that generates data worth tracking, move to a paid monitoring tier. The <a href="/best-geo-tools-2026/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">2026 best GEO tools roundup</a> covers the paid category landscape in full. If you would like independent advice on which entry-level option is appropriate for your specific situation, the <a href="/contact/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEOoptimised team</a> can advise without vendor affiliation.</p>
          </div>

        </div>

        <div class="mt-8 rounded-xl border border-[var(--line)] bg-[var(--bg-2)] px-6 py-4 text-sm text-ink-300">
          <strong class="text-ink-100">A note on the free tool landscape:</strong> Free tier availability across GEO monitoring platforms changes as products evolve. This page describes the general pattern of what free tools can and cannot do, not guaranteed current terms for any specific product. Always verify current free tier terms, query limits, and platform coverage directly with vendors before relying on any tool for your programme.
        </div>
      </section>

