  <!-- FAQ Accordion -->
  <section id="faq" class="container-wide py-20">
    <span class="eyebrow">FAQ</span>
    <h2 class="mt-3 font-display text-3xl font-bold grad-text sm:text-4xl">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="mt-10 max-w-3xl divide-y divide-[var(--line)]">

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button type="button" class="flex w-full items-center justify-between py-5 text-left font-display text-lg font-semibold text-ink-100 hover:text-[var(--accent)] transition-colors" aria-expanded="false">
          <span>Can I actually do GEO effectively with only free tools?</span>
          <svg class="faq-icon ml-4 h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-ink-500 transition-transform duration-200" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M10 5a1 1 0 011 1v3h3a1 1 0 110 2h-3v3a1 1 0 11-2 0v-3H6a1 1 0 110-2h3V6a1 1 0 011-1z"/></svg>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer overflow-hidden transition-all duration-300" style="max-height:0">
          <p class="pb-5 text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">Free tools and manual methods are sufficient to establish a GEO baseline, identify your most significant gaps, and implement structural improvements most likely to improve your citation rate. What they cannot do reliably is track citation frequency at scale over time, benchmark against competitors systematically, or run high-volume prompt testing with statistical confidence. For a brand serious about GEO as an ongoing performance channel, free tools represent a starting point rather than a sustainable long-term measurement infrastructure.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button type="button" class="flex w-full items-center justify-between py-5 text-left font-display text-lg font-semibold text-ink-100 hover:text-[var(--accent)] transition-colors" aria-expanded="false">
          <span>What is the difference between a genuinely free GEO tool and a free tier?</span>
          <svg class="faq-icon ml-4 h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-ink-500 transition-transform duration-200" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M10 5a1 1 0 011 1v3h3a1 1 0 110 2h-3v3a1 1 0 011-1z"/></svg>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer overflow-hidden transition-all duration-300" style="max-height:0">
          <p class="pb-5 text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">A genuinely free tool has no meaningful functional restriction relative to its core GEO use case — Google's Rich Results Test is free without restriction for schema validation. A free tier is a restricted version of a paid product: limited query volumes, capped history, or restricted platform coverage. Both are valuable starting points, but the distinction matters when you are planning your budget. Free tiers are designed to show you the value of the full product.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button type="button" class="flex w-full items-center justify-between py-5 text-left font-display text-lg font-semibold text-ink-100 hover:text-[var(--accent)] transition-colors" aria-expanded="false">
          <span>Is manual AI spot-checking a legitimate GEO method?</span>
          <svg class="faq-icon ml-4 h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-ink-500 transition-transform duration-200" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M10 5a1 1 0 011 1v3h3a1 1 0 110 2h-3v3a1 1 0 011-1z"/></svg>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer overflow-hidden transition-all duration-300" style="max-height:0">
          <p class="pb-5 text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">Manual spot-checking is a legitimate method for qualitative understanding of your AI visibility — identifying how your brand is described, which competitors appear alongside yours, and whether obvious inaccuracies exist. It is not a substitute for systematic tracking because it cannot produce statistically reliable frequency estimates. Use manual checks for qualitative insight and directional evidence; use a monitoring tool for quantitative measurement.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button type="button" class="flex w-full items-center justify-between py-5 text-left font-display text-lg font-semibold text-ink-100 hover:text-[var(--accent)] transition-colors" aria-expanded="false">
          <span>Which free tools should I start with if I have no GEO tooling at all?</span>
          <svg class="faq-icon ml-4 h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-ink-500 transition-transform duration-200" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M10 5a1 1 0 011 1v3h3a1 1 0 110 2h-3v3a1 1 0 011-1z"/></svg>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer overflow-hidden transition-all duration-300" style="max-height:0">
          <p class="pb-5 text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">Start with three things: a manual prompt-testing session across ChatGPT, Perplexity, and Gemini using your most important target queries (recorded in a spreadsheet); Google's Rich Results Test to validate your existing structured data; and a manual review of your Wikipedia entry and Google Knowledge Panel. This combination costs nothing, takes a few hours, and produces a clear picture of your current AI citation status, your most urgent schema gaps, and the state of your entity presence.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button type="button" class="flex w-full items-center justify-between py-5 text-left font-display text-lg font-semibold text-ink-100 hover:text-[var(--accent)] transition-colors" aria-expanded="false">
          <span>When does the budget under £100 per month become worth spending on GEO tools?</span>
          <svg class="faq-icon ml-4 h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-ink-500 transition-transform duration-200" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M10 5a1 1 0 011 1v3h3a1 1 0 110 2h-3v3a1 1 0 011-1z"/></svg>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer overflow-hidden transition-all duration-300" style="max-height:0">
          <p class="pb-5 text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">The right moment to move from free tools to a paid plan is when you have a repeatable optimisation process but cannot scale your measurement — specifically when you are publishing or updating content regularly and need to know whether citation rates are moving, or when a competitor's AI visibility is a meaningful commercial concern requiring systematic competitive data. At under £100 per month, entry-level paid tiers of dedicated GEO monitoring platforms are available and provide measurably better data than free alternatives for ongoing tracking.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button type="button" class="flex w-full items-center justify-between py-5 text-left font-display text-lg font-semibold text-ink-100 hover:text-[var(--accent)] transition-colors" aria-expanded="false">
          <span>Can I use Google Search Console to track GEO performance?</span>
          <svg class="faq-icon ml-4 h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-ink-500 transition-transform duration-200" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M10 5a1 1 0 011 1v3h3a1 1 0 110 2h-3v3a1 1 0 011-1z"/></svg>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer overflow-hidden transition-all duration-300" style="max-height:0">
          <p class="pb-5 text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">Google Search Console does not directly measure AI citation frequency. However, it provides useful indirect signals: traditional organic data informs content quality work that supports GEO, and Google AI Overviews can drive referral traffic visible in GSC. Monitoring traffic to GEO-optimised pages can provide an indirect signal of improvement. GSC is not a GEO measurement tool, but it belongs in any practitioner's free toolkit for the foundational data it provides.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

